The MI6 building in Vauxhall, London. (Photo: Stuart C. Wilson / Getty Images)  Richard Moore, Britainâ€™s new chief of MI6, its external intelligence service, recently said that the â€œclimate emergencyâ€ is the UKâ€™s â€œforemost international foreign policy agenda itemâ€ and that his agency will check on other statesâ€™ commitments on climate. Yet Declassified can reveal that MI6 and the domestic security service, MI5, make it impossible to submit requests under the environmental legislation to which they are subject, rendering it hard to discover these agenciesâ€™ own contributions to climate change. The UKâ€™s Environmental Information Regulations (EIR) were signed into law in 2004. They allow the public to request environmental information from public authorities and oblige them to provide it. Unlike the Freedom of Information Act of 2000, which exempts Britainâ€™s intelligence agencies and special forces from providing information on request, the EIR has no institutional exemptions. But Declassified has made attempts for nine months to obtain information with no success, highlighting further the lack of democratic accountability of Britainâ€™s secret state. Tom Short, a solicitor at Leigh Day specialising in environmental law, told Declassified: â€œThe EIR are clear that public authorities â€” including MI5 and MI6 â€” are required to â€˜take reasonable stepsâ€™ to ensure information is organised so that it can be disseminated to the public and have a duty â€˜to progressively make the informationâ€™ available and accessible to the public through electronic means.â€ But, Short said, â€œThe responses to Declassified reveal a total failure by the relevant authorities to do so.â€ He added: â€œThe treatment of these requests â€” including MI6â€™s complete silence to date and the Home Officeâ€™s refusal to forward on a request to MI5 â€” suggests that the UKâ€™s intelligence services have no grip at all on environmental information matters, despite the likely exten